  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two asteroids labeled A and B. A spaceship on the surface of asteroid A is moving away from the center of asteroid A toward the center of asteroid B.\" src=\"/images/5d76e698afbf366f801760c5b409b1c8.svg\"></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span> of equal density are floating in space far from any other gravitational fields and are separated by a distance that is very large compared to their individual radii. The mass of Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span> is twice the mass of Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span>. A small spaceship is launched away from the center of Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, directed at the center of Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>. The ship experiences no forces after its launch other than the gravitational forces from asteroids <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>. How do the speed of the spaceship and the potential energy of the asteroids-spaceship system just before the spaceship reaches the surface of Asteroid <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span> compare to the values of those quantities at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>? Assume that the distance between asteroids <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span> remains constant while the spaceship is in motion.</p><div class=\"table_wrapper\"><table class=\"tgroup cols:3 colsep:0 frame:none rowsep:0\"><colgroup><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col1 colnum:1 colsep:1\"><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col2 colnum:2\"><col class=\"colspec align:center colname:col3 colnum:3\"></colgroup><thead class=\"thead\"><tr class=\"row rowsep:1\"><th class=\"entry colname:col1\"></th><th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Speed of ship</th><th class=\"entry colname:col3\">Potential energy of system</th></tr></thead><tbody class=\"tbody\"><tr class=\"row\"><td class=\"entry colname:col1\">A</td><td c